  "mitigation_currently_implemented": "Isolate the compromised UbuntuComputer from the network to halt data exfiltration and prevent further lateral movement (quarantine the host or place it on a restricted VLAN).",
  "comments": "Implemented a more robust containment on UbuntuComputer. Steps taken: (1) flushed existing rules and set default policy to DROP for INPUT, OUTPUT, and FORWARD to stop all traffic by default, (2) preserved loopback traffic to maintain local services and diagnostics, (3) allowed established/related connections to avoid breaking ongoing admin/monitoring sessions, (4) allowed essential management traffic within the 192.168.1.0/24 network, (5) hardened outbound control by blocking outbound connections to the attack control host (203.0.113.1:8443) and rejecting all other outbound traffic. This provides containment while enabling incident response. Next actions recommended: apply a restricted management allowlist or dedicated management VLAN, deploy AppArmor for Splunkd, tighten Squid proxy policies for outbound web transfers, enable file integrity monitoring on staging directories, and implement monitoring/alerting for egress, staging, and compression activities. After containment, perform forensics, rotate credentials, and validate restoration; continue to segment networks to limit outbound data transfers.",
  "device_identifier": "UbuntuComputer",
  "commands": [
    "iptables -F; iptables -P INPUT DROP; iptables -P OUTPUT DROP; iptables -P FORWARD DROP; iptables -A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT; iptables -A OUTPUT -o lo -j ACCEPT; iptables -A INPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT; iptables -A OUTPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT; iptables -A OUTPUT -d 192.168.1.0/24 -j ACCEPT; iptables -A INPUT -s 192.168.1.0/24 -j ACCEPT; iptables -A OUTPUT -p tcp -d 203.0.113.1 --dport 8443 -j REJECT; iptables -A OUTPUT -j REJECT"
  ]
}
